  "chunk_index": 39,
  "summary": "Hercule Poirot reveals that David Hunter orchestrated a complex deception to divert suspicion from himself after discovering his blackmailer, Jardine, had been murdered at the Stagg Inn. To create an alibi, Hunter disguised himself as a woman using his sister's clothing and makeup, staging a performance in Room 5 to be seen by a local gossip. He further manipulated his timeline by using a public telephone to coordinate a long-distance call with his sister, Rosalind, making it appear as though he were in London.\n\nPoirot exposes the truth regarding the identity of \"Rosaline Claude.\" The woman was actually Eileen Corrigan, an Irish maid who had survived an air raid alongside Hunter. Hunter had convinced her to impersonate his deceased sister to secure a life of wealth. When the blackmail threatened this deception and Eileen’s conscience caused a mental breakdown, Hunter murdered her by replacing her prescribed bromide sleeping powder with morphine. Upon Poirot presenting a photograph proving Eileen's true identity, Hunter flees the scene. Superintendent Spence arrives to confirm that Hunter has been apprehended.\n\nIn a later scene, Lynn approaches Rolly Claude at his farm. Rolly, burdened by guilt over the deaths of Jardine and Colonel Porter, expresses his belief that he is a criminal. Lynn, however, declares her love for him, dismissing his legal troubles as manslaughter and arguing that the police will remain focused on Hunter for the murders. She insists that she is \"home\" with him, despite the risks.",
